<section xml:id="sec_derivs_using_function_notation">
  <title>Using Function Notation</title>
  <idx><h>derivative</h><h>prime notation</h></idx>
  <p>
    If you have properly defined a function <m>f(x)</m>, you may also make use of the familiar <m>f'(x)</m> notation used in class.
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>f(x) := sin(x) + x^2;</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>sine</h></idx>
    <me>
      \displaystyle f\, := \,x\mapsto \sin \left( x \right) +{x}^{2}
    </me>
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>f'(x);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle \cos \left( x \right) +2\,x
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    This notation is especially useful for evaluating the derivative at a value, without using the <c>subs()</c> command separately.
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      While using <m>m</m> is a common choice for slope, it is a good idea to avoid overusing it in your Maple worksheet.
      You may wish to use <m>m1</m>, <m>m2</m>, etc. when calculating the slopes of many tangent lines.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>slope1 := f'(0);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle slope\mathit{1}\, := \, 1
    </me>
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>slope2 := f'(Pi);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <idx><h>Pi</h></idx>
    <me>
      \displaystyle slope\mathit{2}\, := \, -1 + 2\pi
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    Higher derivatives are also notated in much the same way as in class. 
    <idx><h>derivative</h><h>prime notation!higher derivatives</h></idx>
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>f''(x);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle -\sin \left( x \right) +2
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    Rather than using a string of tick marks, we use a raised exponent in parentheses to specify the <m>n</m>th derivative. This notation can only be used in 2D Math mode.
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>f⁽³⁾(x);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle -\cos \left( x \right)
    </me>
  </p>
</section>